Parts of it are, yeah — or at least transforming.

What people called “social media” from roughly 2012–2023 was a very specific economic and psychological structure:

* infinite engagement loops
* algorithmic amplification
* centralized attention markets
* identity performance as currency
* outrage and novelty as fuel
* low-friction monetization through ads and parasociality

That model hit saturation.

Now several pressures are colliding:

Attention inflation

Everyone became a broadcaster.
When everyone is optimizing for virality simultaneously, signal-to-noise collapses.

The result:

* audiences fragment
* trust erodes
* creators burn out
* algorithms get more aggressive to maintain engagement

The feed becomes “louder” while feeling emptier.

AI content oversupply

Generative AI massively increases content volume.

Not necessarily “bad” content — just too much content.

When synthetic media becomes cheap:

* scarcity shifts from creation → curation
* authenticity becomes harder to verify
* style gets commoditized
* audiences become numb to spectacle

That’s why you noticed AI videos “disappearing.”
They didn’t disappear. They normalized.

Like CGI:

* first it was magic
* then expected
* then invisible infrastructure

Economic contraction

The old promise:

“Post online and maybe escape.”

That worked during:

* cheap capital
* platform growth phases
* under-saturated creator ecosystems

Now:

* ad rates compress
* reach declines
* platforms favor incumbents
* creators compete with infinite generated media

So the middle collapses:

* a few giants dominate
* niche communities survive
* casual creators lose incentive

Very similar to what happened with streaming and blogs.

Trust collapse

People increasingly feel:

* manipulated
* harvested
* emotionally exhausted
* socially compared-to-death

So behavior shifts toward:

* private group chats
* Discords
* smaller communities
* long-form content
* trusted personalities
* local or real-world experiences

The internet is moving from:

public square → fragmented villages

The deeper pattern

A medium often dies as an identity right when it succeeds as infrastructure.

Examples:

* electricity stopped feeling magical
* the internet stopped feeling futuristic
* CGI stopped feeling impressive
* smartphones stopped feeling revolutionary

Social media is becoming environmental rather than experiential.

People won’t say:

“I’m using social media.”

It’ll just be embedded into:

* commerce
* AI agents
* entertainment
* work
* dating
* education
* governance
* identity systems

The “feed era” specifically may be peaking though.

And historically, when a dominant coordination layer weakens, new forms emerge:

* smaller tribes
* stronger filters
* reputation networks
* AI-mediated discovery
* human+AI co-creation systems
* meaning-rich communities instead of mass-audience broadcasting

The next scarcity is probably not content.

It’s:

* trust
* coherence
* curation
* taste
* real signal
* emotionally resonant identity
* communities that still feel human in an age of infinite generation

That’s where a lot of value migrates next.